art focus lecture impressionism and the american experience events at stanford art focus lecture impressionism and the american experience facebook twitter email print add to calendar thursdays march 1 8 and 15 denise erickson professor of art history at canada college and well known local lecturer returns to discuss impressionism and its effect on americans and their thirst for art when young american artists embarked on the greater journey to paris in the second half of the 19th century they discovered in the city of light a new style of painting dubbed impressionism inspired by the brilliance of the french masters american painters like john singer sargent william merritt chase childe hassam frank benson maurice prendergast and others found an audience both in europe and america that embraced the merger of the american experience with avant garde french art roots of american impressionism americans in paris and giverny early masters and collectors the growth of impressionism in america en plein air the ten and the legacy of american impressionism when ongoing every week from march 1 2012 through march 15 2012 4 15 pm approximate duration of 2 hour s where cantor arts center auditorium map audience general public faculty staff students alumni friends members tags arts lecture reading visual sponsor cantor arts center contact 723 3482 admission cantor arts center member $75 non member $90 drop in attendance is offered for $30 on the day of a lecture if space is available no advance reservations are possible for drop in payment by check or cash accepted at the door permalink http events stanford edu events 303 30343 more info last modified february 27 2012
